1. Marginal Plots

1.1. Introduction

In a scatterplot, it is sometimes useful to check the distribution of variables of the X and Y axis. Here Marginal Plots come to the rescue! Using marginal plots, we can add histogram or density plots to the X and Y axes of a scatterplot. The only problem is Marginal plots are not natively supported by ggplot2. But worry not! The ggExtra package (created by Dean Attali) allows one to easily add marginal plots to our usual ggplot2 scatterplots.

1.2. Installation

The ggExtra package is avaialable on CRAN and can be installed directly.

#install
#install.packages("ggExtra")

# library
library(tidyverse)
library(ggExtra)

1.3. How it works

Following is an example of how to add marginal histograms, density curves and boxplots to the scatterplots.

# The mtcars dataset is proposed in R
#head(mtcars)
 
# classic plot :
g = ggplot(mtcars, aes(x=wt, y=mpg, color=cyl, size=cyl)) +
      geom_point() +
      theme(legend.position="none")
 
# with marginal histogram
ggMarginal(g, type="histogram")

# marginal density
ggMarginal(g, type="density")

# marginal boxplot
ggMarginal(g, type="boxplot")

We can customize the margins’ width or their features, and we can show the margin for only one axis.

# Set relative size of marginal plots (main plot 10x bigger than marginals)
ggMarginal(g, type="histogram", size=10)

# Custom marginal plots:
ggMarginal(g, type="histogram", fill = "slateblue", xparams = list(  bins=10))

# Show only marginal plot for x axis
ggMarginal(g, margins = 'x', color="purple", size=4)

2. Annotations

2.1. Introduction

Once our ggplot2 chart is ready, we often need to annotate it to provide more information or highlight a specific part. We can do this easily using the annotate() function.

2.2. How it works

In the first example, let’s add 2 text elements on the plot. We can also adjust the angle of the annotations. If you want to add text from a data.frame, you need to add geom_text!

# basic graph
g <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) + geom_point()
 
# Add text on a specific positions:
g + annotate("text", x = c(2,4.5), y = c(20,25), label = c("label 1", "label 2") , color="blue", size=5 , angle=45, fontface="bold")

Below are 3 examples showing how to add rectangles, segments and arrows to your plot.

# Add rectangles
g + annotate("rect", xmin=c(2,4), xmax=c(3,5), ymin=c(20,10) , ymax=c(30,20), alpha=0.2, color="blue", fill="blue")

# Add segments
g + annotate("segment", x = 1, xend = 3, y = 25, yend = 15, colour = "pink", size=3, alpha=0.6)

# Add arrow
g + annotate("segment", x = 2, xend = 4, y = 15, yend = 25, colour = "purple", size=3, alpha=0.6, arrow=arrow())

We can also add a point and a range around a plot with the “pointrange” geom as follows:

# Add point and range
g + annotate("pointrange", x = 3.5, y = 20, ymin = 12, ymax = 28, colour = "red", size = 1.5, alpha=0.4)

2.3. Ablines

If you need to add ablines, do not use annotate! You can use geom_hline and geom_vline for that purpose.

# Add abline
g + geom_hline(yintercept=25, color="orange", size=1) + geom_vline(xintercept=3, color="orange", size=1)
